reviews.review_text: Undiscovered Gem, Alright Wow! Thanks to Grateful Dead of The Day, I decided to jump in and give this one a listen. Of course I went to the Charlie Miller version, my auto-default mechanism firmly in place. Can't believe more haven't reviewed and commented on this one. I will however quote allfalldown, who commented on the more downloaded SBD here, one year ago today coincidently, that "I've never understood why this show isn't widely renowned, but maybe that's why I also love so much.......an undiscovered gem." It sure is! The setlist might not draw you in, but trust me, it's well worth it. Although I first saw the Dead with Brent, and I love Brent, I've always been more partial to Keith's piano, so naturally I've always loved Bruce's contribution to the band. Man, does he sparkle on this one, and he's very high up in the mix. You can't underestimate the fire he lit under the guys on a nightly basis. BIODTL elicited as good a laugh from me as it did Bob at the botched opening, and what's wrong with that, really? Bruce then refuses to quit the tune, the band takes a few seconds before they realize he's still going, and awkwardly they follow suit, but it all ends well. CC sliding into It Takes A Lot is another first set beauty. The second set is all well played and Bob seems to give S&D and Throwing Stones different vocal emphasis, resulting in versions a bit different than what I'm used to use hearing. Anyways, I've always considered 06/17/91 and 09/10/91 as the best of that year Put this one up there too.
